Transaction-Receipt Matcher¶

ABSTRACT¶

Our customers want the ability to automatically match receipt images to the associated transaction within the Banking app. Each of the data items returned from the external supplier was compared against the same data from the transaction, and a ‘transaction-receipt’ matching vector was created. The elements of the matching vector will be produced in different ways depending on the underlying data types being matched . We want to build a model to learn which matching features are the most successful. The ultimate goal is to match a single receipt to the correct transaction given a number of possible transactions however, given real world considerations, we want to sort the possible transactions for a given receipt in order of likelihood of being the correct transaction.

Aproach¶

First we will explore the data ,decide the evaluation metric in conjunction with Business objectve ,followed by some feature engineering that feeds into the model and finalize the baseline model after running a series of experiments . After finalizing the baseline model , we will attempt to improve the model to lift the performance metric(Discussed in later section) .

Deciding Evaluation Metric¶

  • So which model will perform best in this use case?
  • Simple accuracy is bad metric here due to highly imbalanced data as randomly labeling as all incorrect matching the accuracy will be very high.
  • Recall = true positives/(true positives + false negatives)
  • Precison = true positives/(true positives + false positives) - Recall could be looked as ability of model to correctly label all true positives and precison is the fraction of relevant instances among the retrieved instances.
  • Both of these are important but the objective is to to get a high Recall, so that all relevant correct matchings could be found from all the actual possible correct matches.

Baseline¶

  • Create a baseline model using matching vector as feature.
  • Starting with simple logistic regression,KNN ,Decision Tree ,Naive Bayes and and then ensemble techniques like Random Forest and xgboost model.
  • Xgboost model produces best result for baseline, so moving forward we will be tuning the xgboost model only.

BASELINE MODEL¶

Using Cross validation to see the best model

In [16]:
data['label']= (data.matched_transaction_id == data.feature_transaction_id).astype(int)
x,y = data[list(data.columns[4:])], data.label
x=x.drop(['label'], axis=1)  
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42,shuffle=True)

logreg_cv = LogisticRegression(solver='lbfgs', max_iter=1000)
dt_cv=DecisionTreeClassifier()
rf=RandomForestClassifier()
svc_cv=SVC()
nb_cv=GaussianNB()
cv_dict = {0: 'Random Forest', 1: 'Decision Tree',2:'KNN',3:'SVC',4:'Naive Bayes',5:'Logistic Regression'}
cv_models=[rf,dt_cv,nb_cv,rf,logreg_cv]

### cross validation

for i,model in enumerate(cv_models):
    print("{} accuracy: {}".format(cv_dict[i],cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv=10, scoring ='accuracy').mean()))
for i,model in enumerate(cv_models):
    print("{} Recall: {}".format(cv_dict[i],cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv=10, scoring ='recall').mean()))

Convert the dataset into an optimized data structure called Dmatrix that XGBoost supports and gives it acclaimed performance and efficiency gains.

In [17]:
    
train = xgboost.DMatrix(X_train, label=y_train)
test = xgboost.DMatrix(X_test, label=y_test)
watchlist = [(test, 'eval'), (train, 'train')]

xgb_params = {
            'objective': 'binary:logistic',
            'tree_method': 'gpu_hist',
            'max_depth': 2, 
            'eta':0.1,
            'silent':1,
            'subsample':0.5,
            'colsample_bytree': 0.05,
            
}

clf = xgboost.train( xgb_params,train, num_boost_round=10000, )

preds = clf.predict(test)

MODEL IMPROVEMENTS¶

DATA IMBALANCE FEATURE ENGINEERING:¶
  • The difference in weights will influence the classification of the classes during the training phase. The whole purpose is to penalize the misclassification made by the minority class by setting a higher class weight and at the same time reducing weight for the majority class.
  • The best method would to have weighted loss, meaning if rare class is missclassifed the model would penalised more.
  • We would specify a weight ratio, say 8.
In [20]:
data['label']= (data.matched_transaction_id == data.feature_transaction_id).astype(int)
x,y = data[list(data.columns[4:])], data.label
x=x.drop(['label'], axis=1)  
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42,shuffle=True)
    
train = xgboost.DMatrix(X_train, label=y_train)
test = xgboost.DMatrix(X_test, label=y_test)
watchlist = [(test, 'eval'), (train, 'train')]

xgb_params = {
            'objective': 'binary:logistic',
            'tree_method': 'gpu_hist',
            'max_depth': 2, 
            'eta':0.1,
            'silent':1,
            'subsample':0.5,
            'colsample_bytree': 0.05,
            'scale_pos_weight':8,
}

clf = xgboost.train( xgb_params,train )

preds = clf.predict(test)

print(classification_report((y_test),preds.round(0)))

labels = ['Match-No', 'Match-Yes']

cm = sklearn.metrics.confusion_matrix((y_test),(preds.round(0).astype(int)))
 

ax= plt.subplot()
sns.heatmap(cm.astype(int), annot=True,fmt='g', ax = ax); #annot=True to annotate cells

# labels, title and ticks
ax.set_xlabel('Predicted labels');ax.set_ylabel('True labels'); 
ax.set_title('Confusion Matrix'); 
ax.xaxis.set_ticklabels(labels); ax.yaxis.set_ticklabels(labels);

Next steps:¶

  • We can try to select best hyperparmeters for the xgb model we are using to further improve the performance using Sklearn's scikit-optimize or HyperOpt that uses Bayesian Optimisation to get best model parameters.

  • Also we can try to use stacking technique to combine classifiers and observe results.

SUMMARY:¶

  • A minimum viable product i.e a good classifier using XgBoost which is able to match the correct ‘transaction-receipt’ with high confidence was trained and saved.
  • We chose 'Recall' as the evaluation metric.
  • Hyper-Parameter search is hard for such kind of imbalanced data and low number of samples.
  • Due to limited information on current feature vector, feature engineering is difficult and also outlier treatment was not carried out.
  • Creating an ensemble of models can have resulted in little better performance but it's hard to deploy, so didn't attempt ensemble of models .
